klepet33319 wrote:
&gt;      For anyone interested in this question please go to:
&gt;                   http://world.choshuya.co.jp/
&gt;      If you sign up for their member&#39;s only page they have several 
&gt; very high end pieces including a Soumin Futatokoromono, the menuki 
&gt; which exhibit exactly the post arangement I am asking about.  As 
&gt; Soumin studied under Goto masters and was one of the founders of 
&gt; Machibori I find it interesting he here is using the open/closed end 
&gt; posts such as the mainline Goto masters often used.  Having come 
&gt; across an article by Thomas B. Buttweiler, &#39;The History of Pre-Edo 
&gt; Menuki&#39;, Token TaiKai 1976, on pp. 62 & 63 the following is noted:
&gt;
&gt;      &quot;By the end of the Dolmen Period the Tsuka ornaments had been 
&gt; modified to function as Mekugi.  Because of the constraints placed on 
&gt; Menuki, the size was reduced and the design became rounded and more 
&gt; compact.  These first Menuki were made to be an integral part of the 
&gt; Mekugi.  The solid pin of one Menuki extended through the Mekugi-Ana 
&gt; of the sword and was capped on the other side of the Tsuka by the 
&gt; hollow cylindrical pin of the matching Menuki.  This hollow-solid 
&gt; cylindrical arrangement remained standard in the Goto School for five 
&gt; hundred years after the Menuki ceased to be an integral part of the 
&gt; Mekugi.
&gt;
&gt;      By the end of the Nara Period the wrapped Tsuka came into common 
&gt; use.  This inovation sounded the death knell of the integral Mekugi-
&gt; Menuki.  Since the tight wrapping allowed virtually no space between 
&gt; adjacent turns, the Mekugi-Menuki had to be mounted over the Tsuka-
&gt; Ito.  The softness of the wrap allowed the pins to move relative to 
&gt; one another.  The subsequent metal to metal wear, resulted in loss of 
&gt; adhesion, with the possible disappearance of one Menuki.  An 
&gt; alternate method of external mounting was attempted.  This consisted 
&gt; of mounting the two Menuki on an independent wooden Mekugi.  The 
&gt; mounting was accomplished using a hollow cylindrical pin in each 
&gt; Menuki, to fit over the Mekugi proper.  This approach was doomed to 
&gt; failure for the same reasons stated earlier.  The double hollow 
&gt; cylindrical pin arrangement, remained as a vestige of this mounting 
&gt; technique, until the Muromachi Period, in the Ezo School.
&gt;
&gt;      These two attempts at using externally mounted Menuki, either 
&gt; attached to or made part of the Mekugi, can only be classed as 
&gt; transitional.  From a functional standpoint they were doomed to 
&gt; failure from the onset.
&gt;
&gt;      Even though the Menuki could not be mounted as part of the 
&gt; mekugi, tradition dictated that the Menuki be retained.  They were 
&gt; inserted under the wraps using the rather feeble justifiaction that 
&gt; their use improved the warriors grip on the sword.
&gt;
&gt;      Aside from the debate over the dubious functionality of wrapped 
&gt; Menuki, they had, by the end of the Heian Period, become an 
&gt; established member of the compliment of Kodogu.  Their status has 
&gt; remained, except for variation of motif, unchanged up to the present 
&gt; day&quot;.
&gt;
&gt;      I still have to wonder if there is a known justification for the 
&gt; inclusion of this arrangement or if it is simply a nod to tradition?
